Theming in CSS with Sass
Theming in CSS refers to the process of creating different visual styles or skins for a website or application. It allows you to customize the appearance of your website without having to rewrite the entire CSS codebase.

Sass is a CSS preprocessor that offers several features that make theming easier, including variables, nesting, and mixins. By using Sass variables to store theme-specific values, you can create themes that can be easily switched between.

Creating a Theme Switcher
Here's a basic example of a theme switcher using Sass variables:

HTML:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Theme Switcher</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <button id="theme-toggle">Toggle Theme</button>
    <div class="content">
        <h1>This is a heading</h1>
        <p>This is some content.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
Use code with caution.

Sass (style.scss):

Code snippet
:root {
    --primary-color: #000;
    --secondary-color: #fff;
    --background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

body {
    background-color: var(--background-color);
    color: var(--primary-color);
}

h1 {
    color: var(--secondary-color);
}

#theme-toggle {
    cursor: pointer;
}

#theme-toggle:hover {
    background-color: var(--primary-color);
    color: var(--secondary-color);
}

.dark-theme {
    --primary-color: #fff;
    --secondary-color: #000;
    --background-color: #333;
}
Use code with caution.

JavaScript (script.js):

JavaScript
const themeToggle = document.getElementById('theme-toggle');
const root = document.documentElement;

themeToggle.addEventListener('click', () => {
    root.classList.toggle('dark-theme');
});
Use code with caution.

Explanation
Sass Variables: The :root selector defines global variables for the primary and secondary colors, as well as the background color.
Theme Styles: The body, h1, and #theme-toggle elements use these variables to set their styles.
Dark Theme Class: The .dark-theme class overrides the default variable values, creating a dark theme.
JavaScript: The JavaScript code toggles the .dark-theme class on the root element, switching between the light and dark themes.
By using Sass variables and a JavaScript-based theme switcher, you can easily create and manage multiple themes for your website, allowing users to customize their experience.